msDesc.head: Homilies and saints' lives, in Old English

summary.seg: Cambridge, University Library, MS Ii.1.33 (hereafter CUL MS Ii.1.33) is a remarkable manuscript, in that it offers unique evidence for the transitional period between Old English and Middle English. Compiled in the second half of the twelfth century, it stands out for being one of the latest extant collections containing Old English texts, demonstrating the linguistic, cultural and historical transformations of its time. Furthermore, its significance lies not only in its contents, but also in its complex history of compilation, usage and subsequent scholarly engagement.

The manuscript primarily consists of texts by Ælfric of Eynsham (c. 950-c. 1010), a monk and abbot known for his large amount of Old English religious prose, such as his two sets of Catholic Homilies and his Lives of Saints. It also includes some penitential material towards the end: three anonymous texts and an Old English translation of Alcuin's De uirtutibus et uitiis, chapters 1-13. In the manuscript, some Ælfrician pieces are presented only as passion narratives, suggesting that the book might have originally been intended as a Passional.

The manuscript underwent several stages of development, with contributions from at least two but possibly up to four scribes, based on both palaeographical and linguistic considerations. The current order of texts does not reflect their order of copying; rather, the manuscript was built around a core, and the first four texts that appear may in fact have been written last. Some of the texts that were copied earliest focus on the apostles, while some later ones, copied by a different scribe, address saints in a Church-year order. Subsequent additions transformed the manuscript's character, turning it from an 'Apostolic Passional' to a 'Saintly Reader', and ultimately to a miscellaneous collection of religious texts.

CUL MS Ii.1.33 is an invaluable resource for understanding the linguistic transition from Old English to Middle English. Although the primary language of the manuscript is Old English, it incorporates some Middle English features, particularly in later additions and alterations. These linguistic changes are particularly evident in orthography and vocabulary, and offer insights into how these scribes engaged with older texts while adapting them to their contemporary linguistic context. Notably, one scribe contributed a marginal Middle English passage adapted from a Latin source, alongside two marginal passages in Old French, highlighting the multilingual environment of the period (see ff. 70v and 120r). The manuscript also shows evidence of deliberate preservation and emendation. Scribes updated texts linguistically to reflect contemporary usage while sometimes reverting to older forms, indicating a complex relationship with the linguistic heritage of Old English. This blend of conservation and adaptation underscores the manuscript's role as a bridge between Old English and Middle English.

The origins and medieval provenance of CUL MS Ii.1.33 have been widely debated. The manuscript is thought to have been compiled in a south-eastern scriptorium, potentially at Canterbury or Rochester. Another possible origin is Ely, given the manuscript's later association with St Æthelthryth, Ely's patron saint. There may also be a link to Barnwell Priory, on the outskirts of Cambridge. Although direct evidence to link the manuscript to these locations is limited, the manuscript's emphasis on specific saints and its inclusion of particular texts align with these ecclesiastical centres. Such associations further situate the manuscript within broader ecclesiastical and cultural networks in medieval England - and the possibility that it was a commissioned work or a gift between monasteries reflects the interconnectedness of these institutions. However, the absence of conclusive proof leaves room for further study and speculation, as much for the manuscript's origins as its intended purposes, which also remain uncertain.

Unlike other homiletic collections designed explicitly for preaching, this manuscript seems to be more associated with private or communal reading. The lack of expository content typical of sermons supports this hypothesis. As new sections were added, the manuscript's character evolved, adapting to changing needs. For example, its emphasis on saints and the Church-year order suggests a devotional or educational function. Certainly, though, CUL MS Ii.1.33 provides critical evidence of the continued copying and use of Old English texts long after the Norman Conquest. While the production of new vernacular texts declined in the twelfth century, manuscripts like this one demonstrate an enduring demand for Old English religious works. This interest may have stemmed from a desire to preserve Anglo-Saxon heritage or from the practical use of these texts in devotional and educational settings. The manuscript's multilingual character, with Latin and Old French alongside both Old English and Middle English, highlights the complex linguistic environment of post-Conquest England. Although an inscription on f. 29r indicates a period of neglect (a common fate for Old English texts after the Norman Conquest), evidence of renewed interest in the manuscript's contents is extensive: glosses, additions, running titles and marginal annotations, in Middle English and Latin, were made during the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries, possibly for instructional purposes, and point to ongoing engagement with the manuscript over many decades.

Such interest persists to this day. Following the Dissolution of the Monasteries and the dispersal of their libraries, the manuscript came into the hands of Matthew Parker (1504-1575), archbishop of Canterbury, and was one of twenty-five manuscripts he donated to Cambridge University Library in 1574. George Hickes listed it alongside its texts in 1689, while Humfrey Wanley's companion volume to Hickes' later Thesaurus in 1705 provided more detailed information, including incipits and/or explicits. In 1957, Neil Ker offered the most comprehensive description of the manuscript up to that time in his catalogue of manuscripts containing Old English. Subsequent scholarship, including the work of Elaine Treharne (1998), Oliver M. Traxel (2004), John Frankis (2007) and Orietta Da Rold (2010), has continued to refine our understanding of the manuscript's content and significance. Standard editions of Ælfrician texts, such as those by Peter Clemoes, Malcolm R. Godden, and Walter W. Skeat, have drawn extensively from CUL MS Ii.1.33. The manuscript's four non-Ælfrician texts have also attracted editorial attention, particularly Anna Maria Luiselli Fadda's edition of two anonymous Old English homilies (1977) and Susan G. Youngs' dissertation on the final text appearing in the manuscript: the poem Instructions for Christians (1995).

That the manuscript has continued to attract scholarly attention over a period of more than eight and a half centuries attests to its enduring significance both as a cultural artefact and a subject of academic enquiry. As one of the last manuscripts to be made that contains text in Old English, and partially glossed in the vernacular language that evolved thereafter, it provides a bridge between the language and culture of pre- and post-Conquest England, offering a distinctive perspective on the preservation and transformation of this country's linguistic and literary heritage.

Prof. Dr. Oliver M. Traxel
Professor of English Language and Linguistics
University of Stavanger

Directions for reciting the Penitential Psalms.

Six lines of text inserted by one of the text scribes in a blank space at the end of Quire 8 (see Ker, but cf. Traxel). This is a translation of the section Primus usus psalmorum of Alcuin's De psalmorum usu liber.

extent.seg: v + + 1 + 226 + iii leaves. There are two blank endleaf guards, foliated 'i bis' and 'vi bis'. They have not been counted as leaves in this statement of extent.

foliation.p: i-ii, ii bis, iii-iv + 1 + 2-227 + v, v bis, vi

Folio numbers written in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the recto side of each leaf by an unidentified hand of the 20th century (probably first half). The endleaves were numbered by Jayne Ringrose (c. 2013, presumably in preparation for the manuscript's digitisation).
Page numbers written in Parkerian red/orange crayon in the upper right-hand corner of the recto side of each leaf only (see Provenance for further details).

collation.p: The manuscript comprises 28 quires, typically of eight leaves; in some, two singletons are used in place of a bifolium (see Quires 10, 12 and 21). The two inserted leaves in Quire 20 are, by contrast, conjoined: a folded bifolium that has been stab sewn behind ff. 151|157. Two parchment stubs are found after Quire 1. The first of these connects with f. 1, a leaf probably added in the 16th century to accommodate a table of contents (rather than an originally blank leaf that was used for this purpose). The second connects only with a stub preceding f. 1: since it bears no evidence of having contained text or having been prepared for ruling, the likelihood is that this is the remnant of a single leaf that had previously formed the pastedown or a blank endleaf at the beginning of the manuscript.

The manuscript comprises perhaps five codicological units. Quire signatures on Quires 8-13 ('i'-'vi') and 15 ('viii') indicate that these formed the core of the manuscript (with Quire 16), to which further quires were then added, both before and after. These divisions are indicated below by semi-colons. Owing to the way in which the manuscript developed, these do not always coincide with textual divisions. For instance, the first two leaves of Quire 16 provided the space for the completion of Ælfric's sermon on the remembrance of saints; a new hand takes over at this point, filling the remainder of the quire with his homilies, which then continue on subsequent quires. The quire numbers do not continue, but are supplanted by catchwords. Similarly, the quires inserted at the beginning of the manuscript contain Ælfric's preface to and part-translation of Genesis, which ends on f. 24v, the penultimate leaf of Quire 3. Another hand continued with homilies to the end of that quire, with three leaves (Quire 4) being added to provide the necessary space to accommodate it. The rest of f. 28v was left blank, perhaps because the text on Quires 5 and Quires 6-7 (each themselves a codicological unit) had already been copied. However, the current order of quires is not necessarily the original arrangement: a note by a 13th-century hand on f. 29r suggests that Quire 5 might once have been placed at the beginning of the volume.

signatures.p: Quire signatures in the 'core' part of the manuscript, Quires 8-13 ('i'-'vi') and 15 ('viii'), indicating that these were produced first and the remaining quires inserted around them. Written in ink in the centre of the bottom margin on the verso of the last leaf of the quire.

catchwords.seg: Catchwords on Quires 18-19, 21, 25-27 (those on Quires 20, 22-24 probably cropped). Written in ink in the bottom margin on the verso of the last leaf of the quire.

supportDesc.condition: The leaves have been trimmed. Spine leather severely cracked, with losses at the foot; joints beginning to split, with boards loosening at the head and foot.

layout.p: For further detailed description of pricking, ruling, bounding lines, written space and other features of layout, see Bremmer and Dekker (2013) and Da Rold (2010) (see Source).

p.seg: Folios 2r-25v: ruled in leadpoint, frame and line, single columns, 24 lines to the page, written above top line.
Folios 26r-28v: ruled in leadpoint, frame and line, single columns, 26-28 lines to the page, written above top line.

Folios 53r-120v: ruled in leadpoint, frame and line, single columns, 22-24 lines to the page, written above top line.
Folios 120v-227v: ruled in leadpoint, frame and line, single columns, 24-26 lines to the page, written above top line.

handDesc.handNote: As Bremmer and Dekker note, 'There are various reconstructions of the arrangements of scribal hands, which are related to the history of the compilation of the manuscript, and throughout the manuscript there are interlinear corrections in what appear to be contemporaneous hands.' Their description (ASMMF, 2013) provides a summary of and references to the key publications (see Source).

handNote.p: Two (but possibly three or even four) hands, all writing English vernacular minuscule: Hand 1 copied ff. 2r-36v and 120v-227v, in stages - and was also responsible for copying Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 367, Part 1 (see Treharne (1998); Hand 2 (Ker) copied ff. 37r-120v (Ker (1957), p. 27). Some scholars have identified other hands in the manuscript (e.g. Schipper (1983, p. 286), who divides Ker's Hand 2 into two stints, 'Scribe B' copying ff. 53r-120v, and 'Scribe C' filling in ff. 37r-52v), but this has been rejected by Da Rold (2010) (see for further discussion), who pointed instead to correlation between Ker's identifications and the patterns of ruling and signatures/catchwords found in these stints.

decoNote.p: Two- to four-line initials in red, occasionally with additional foliate decoration or internal ornamental voids. Initials are somewhat more elaborate in the 'core' section of the manuscript - note in particular the zoomorphic additions to the initial on f. 61r - but the leaf / vine extensions continue into subsequent quires, indicating that they were completed in one stint, and / or by the same hand, or efforts were made to ensure a consistency of presentation. Some initials executed in green on ff. 214r-227v.

decoDesc.decoNote: Running titles in plummet in the top margins (now almost invisible). Attributed to Glossator B by Traxel (2004, p. 149).

note.p: Marginal insertions and corrections in Latin and English by the text scribe (Ker's Hand 1) on ff. 25r, 31r, 36r, 70v, 77v, 82r, 82v, 95v, 120r, 120v-122v, 123r, 124v, 211r-213v, 219r, 224v and 225r. Notes in French in the bottom margins of ff. 70v and 120r (see Traxel (2004)). These annotations are listed (and in many cases have been transcribed) by Da Rold (2010).

Annotation in Latin, partly trimmed, datable to the 13th/14th century in the top margin of f. 29r: [Hoc uolumen] continet multam copiam sermonum in anglico. | non appreciatum propter ydioma incognitum.
Annotations in English and Latin by 14th-century hands on ff. 37r-42v.

'Parkerian' table of contents (f. 1r), written by a 16th-century hand (see Provenance). Different 16th-century hands added the rubrics (upper margin) and 'homiliae . 51 .' (lower margin), and further additions were made by 17th-century hands, including references to 'Serm. Cath'), as well as 19th-century additions in pencil by John Mitchell Kemble (see below).
Marginal and interlinear annotations and underlinings by 16th-century and later hands throughout, mainly in Latin but also including Hebrew (f. 114v) and Greek (f. 167v).

Marginal annotations and underlining in pencil and ink (ff. 24v, 52v, ?98r-99r, ?114r-117r, 120v, 139v, 155v, 161v-168v, 175v-179v, ?208r, 208v-210r, 211v, 217v, 218v, 223v), by the hand of Wheelocke, Abraham, 1593-1653 Abraham Wheelocke (c. 1593-1653) , University Librarian 1629-53 (see Schipper (1983), Lucas (2006), ASMMF (2013)).

binding.p: Brown full leather covering over pasteboards, 17th-century. Border and corner fleurons blind-tooled on the cover. Pastedowns (now lifted) recycled from a copy of Pablo de Santa Maria, Bishop of Burgos, Dialogus Pauli et Sauli contra Judæos, sive Scrutinium scripturarum (see ff. ii bis and v bis). Former classmarks on ii bis verso indicate that this leaf had previously been bound upside down, relative to the text it contains. Repaired by J.P. Gray and sonJ.P. Gray and Son, Cambridge, July 1958: stamp on front pastedown, with date supplied by H.L. Pink. Spine label ('Tracts M.S.'), gold-tooled on red leather, retained on front pastedown. Title and classmark tooled in gold on the spine ('Aelfric's Homilies' and 'Ii.1.33'), presumably added when repaired.

origin.p: Several possible places of origin have been proposed. Treharne (1998, pp. 240-44) suggests a South-Eastern origin, probably Christ Church, Canterbury or Rochester. Schipper (1983, pp. 291-92), building on Godden (1967, p. 23), argues that part of the manuscript was copied at the cathedral priory at Ely, on the basis of the presence of text on St Æthelthryth from the Vita sanctorum on ff. 34v-36v, which could have constituted the central starting point for the process of copying. Traxel (2004, p. 207) suggests a possible compilation originally from St Augustine's, Canterbury and then Ely. Mary Richards' review (2007) of Traxel re-proposes a possible Rochester provenance. Frankis (2007) proposes a connection with the priory of Barnwell, a house of Augustinian canons near Cambridge, which was dedicated to St Giles.

provenance.p: Matthew Parker (1504-1575) Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 , archbishop of Canterbury: partial pagination in characteristic red/orange crayon. It is unknown from where Parker acquired the manuscript. Bremmer and Dekker (2013) suggest the possibility that her may have found it in Ely during his time as canon there 1541-1554, or during his visitation in 1563 (see Schipper (1983)).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1574 by Matthew Parker (1504-1575) Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575, archbishop of Canterbury. No. 10 in the list of 25 'Libri Scripti in pergameno' published to commemorate Parker's gift (see Early catalogues of manuscripts, up to c. 1600). As Ker noted (1957, p. 27), the manuscript was listed among those bequeathed by Parker to Corpus Christi College, Cambridge, but was never there (cf. M.R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the manuscripts in the library of Corpus Christi College Cambridge (Cambridge: University Press, 1912), vol. 1, p. xxxvii, under S(17), against which is added 'deest J[ohn] P[arker]' and 'wanting at ye first, Jo. Parker').
